NHANES: HPV Infection by Sexual Behavior

Jennifer Spencer

9/8/2019

This file imports 7 cycles (14 years worth) of data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey.

The file proceeds as follows:

[1] We import the relevant files from raw NHANES files.

[2] We create a matched dataset containing all years and only the variables of interest.

[3] We define sexual behavior categories based on survey data

[4] We define HPV infection status based on laboratory data

[5] We compared HPV prevalence by sexual behavior data and save these estimates to put into a model

Import Data Files: NHANES 2003-2016

  1. Demographic data file 2015-2016, 2013-2014, 2011-2012, 2009-2010, 2007-2008, 2005-2006, 2003-2004 We will use ID, Age, Gender, and 2-year exam-based survey weights

These variables had the same name in all years, so we create a program to extra these an loop over each year. (Program shown but the loops are hidden for the sake of space)

# # # # Import & Select # # # #

      ## Demographic Variables  ##

f.demo_clean       <- function(data, year) {
  out_data         <- data   %>% select(      SEQN,  #ID
                                     "age"=RIDAGEYR, #Age
                                  "gender"=RIAGENDR, #Gender
                                      "wt"=WTMEC2YR, #weight
                                     "psu"=SDMVPSU,  #PSU
                                  "strata"=SDMVSTRA)  #Strata 
  out_data$year    <- year
  
  return(out_data)
            }

  1. Questionnaire data file 2015-2016, 2013-2014, 2011-2012, 2009-2010, 2007-2008, 2005-2006, 2003-2004: Sexual History

We will use ID and sexual history variables. Some of these change name/wording slightly across years - the differences in this wording are relatively minor. However, in 2003-2004 they did not separately ask if participants had ever had sex with a man/woman, only the number. So in 2003-2004 there is no missingness in number but in later years they make it a two-part question and people who say “no” to the “ever” quesiton are missing in the “number of partners” questions.

So we correct this in the original data sets and save the variables we are interested in: number of male partners lifetime and in past year, number of female parters lifetime and past year, whether participant has ever had sex, and self-reported orientation.

          ## Sexual Behavior ##
#Pull in sexual history variables

f.sex_clean        <- function(data, year) {

                if(year==2016) { 
                  
                  data$SXD101[data$SXQ700==2]     <- 0         # ever male asked as a separate q 2010-2016
                  data$SXQ130[data$SXQ709==2]     <- 0         # ever female asked as a separate q 2010-2016
                  
    out_data         <- data   %>% select(           SEQN, #ID
                                      "ever_sex"  = SXD021,     #ever had sex
                                     "num_m_ever" = SXD101,     #   male partners lifetime 
                                     "num_m_py"   = SXD450,     #   male partners past year
                                    "num_f_ever"  = SXQ130,     # female partners lifetime 
                                      "num_f_py"  = SXQ490,     # female partners past year
                                    "orientation" = SXQ295 )     #orientation
  }
            else if (year>2008) {
                  data$SXD101[data$SXQ700==2]     <- 0         # ever male asked as a separate q 2010-2016
                  data$SXQ130[data$SXQ709==2]     <- 0         # ever female asked as a separate q 2010-2016

     out_data         <- data   %>% select(           SEQN, #ID
                                      "ever_sex"   = SXD021,     #ever had sex
                                      "num_m_ever" = SXD101,     #   male partners lifetime 
                                     "num_m_py"    = SXD450,     #   male partners past year
                                    "num_f_ever"   = SXQ130,     # female partners lifetime 
                                      "num_f_py"   = SXQ490,     # female partners past year
                                    "orientation"  = SXQ294)      #orientation
 }
  
             else if (year>2004) {
               
               
                  data$SXQ101[data$SXQ021==2]     <- 0         # single question for both M/F 
                  data$SXQ130[data$SXQ021==2]     <- 0         # single question for both M/F 
                           
     out_data         <- data   %>% select(           SEQN, #ID
                                      "ever_sex"  = SXQ021,     #ever had sex
                                     "num_m_ever" = SXQ101,     #   male partners lifetime 
                                     "num_m_py"   = SXQ450,     #   male partners past year
                                    "num_f_ever"  = SXQ130,     # female partners lifetime 
                                      "num_f_py"  = SXQ490,     # female partners past year
                                    "orientation" = SXQ294)      #orientation
             } 
           
                          else  {
                            
                            
                  data$SXQ100[data$SXQ020==2]     <- 0     #single question for both M/F 
                  data$SXQ130[data$SXQ020==2]     <- 0     #single question for both M/F   
  
     out_data         <- data   %>% select(           SEQN, #ID
                                      "ever_sex"  = SXQ020,     #ever had sex
                                     "num_m_ever" = SXQ100,     #   male partners lifetime 
                                     "num_m_py"   = SXQ120,     #   male partners past year
                                    "num_f_ever"  = SXQ130,     # female partners lifetime 
                                      "num_f_py"  = SXQ150,     # female partners past year
                                    "orientation" = SXQ294)      #orientation
  } 

                                
  out_data$year    <- year
  
  return(out_data)
}

Then we combine all three of these data sets together by patient ID. To account for survey weights properly, we can’t drop anyone but we do want to identify the subgroup that we are including. So we identify them and check the number included in each year.

We then incorporate the survey weights from NHANES to reflect the US population

# # # # Survey Weights  # # # #

#Create our survey design variable 
nhanes_design      <- svydesign(id      = ~psu,
                                strata  = ~strata,
                                weights = ~wt,
                                nest    = TRUE,
                                data    = full_nhanes)

#tell it who our subsample is 
hpv_sample        <- subset(nhanes_design, sample==1)

Sexual History Data

Now we define women based on their sexual behavior data, favoring recent data such that:

Category Description
Not Sexually Active No previous sexual partners
Heterosexual Only opposite-sex partners OR majority of all partners or past year partner is opposite-sex with no more than 2 previous same-sex partners
Homosexual Only same-sex partners OR majority of all partners or past year most recent partner is same-sex with no more than 2 previous opposite-sex partners
Bisexual 1+ same-sex and 1+ opposite-sex partners in the previous year OR 3+ same-sex and 3+ opposite-sex lifetime partners OR 3+ same-sex partners lifetime and an opposite-sex partner in the previous year OR 3+ opposite-sex partners lifetime and a same-sex partner in the previous year 
#First, clean up some of the variables that are conditional questions: 
full_nhanes$num_m_ever[full_nhanes$ever_sex==2] <- 0
full_nhanes$num_f_ever[full_nhanes$ever_sex==2] <- 0
full_nhanes$num_m_py  [full_nhanes$ever_sex==2] <- 0
full_nhanes$num_f_py  [full_nhanes$ever_sex==2] <- 0

#If you said you didn't know, replace as NA
full_nhanes$num_m_ever[full_nhanes$num_m_ever==77777 |full_nhanes$num_m_ever==99999] <- NA
full_nhanes$num_f_ever[full_nhanes$num_f_ever==77777 |full_nhanes$num_f_ever==99999] <- NA



#Now define bisexual
#First by lifetime behavior
full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$num_m_ever>0  & full_nhanes$num_f_ever<3 ]    <- "heterosexual" 
full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$num_f_ever>0  & full_nhanes$num_m_ever<3 ]    <- "homosexual"

#Then, replace favoring recency (if you haven't had 3 partners of one type we give preference to your more recent behavior)
full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$num_f_py>0]      <- "homosexual"
full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$num_m_py>0]      <- "heterosexual"

#Finally if you haven't had sex with anyone this year and have fewer than 3 of each, 
      #we default to which group you've had more sex with, with ties going to lesbians
full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$num_f_py==0  & full_nhanes$num_m_py==0 &
                  full_nhanes$num_m_ever<3 & full_nhanes$num_m_ever<3 & 
                    (full_nhanes$num_f_ever>=full_nhanes$num_m_ever)]       <- "homosexual"

#Then change identify as bisexual if you've had three of both or one of each in the previous year
full_nhanes$behav[(full_nhanes$num_f_ever>=3 & full_nhanes$num_m_ever>=3) | 
                  (full_nhanes$num_f_py>=1   & full_nhanes$num_m_ever>=3) | 
                  (full_nhanes$num_f_ever>=3 & full_nhanes$num_m_py>=1)  ]   <- "bisexual"

full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$num_f_py>=1     & full_nhanes$num_m_py>=1  ]   <- "bisexual"
#If you've never had sex you are in the none category
full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$ever_sex==2]                                   <- "none"

full_nhanes$behav[full_nhanes$sample==0]                                     <- NA

Sexual Behavior Graphs

We can make graphs to show how each of our behavior categories (in our primary definition) split out by what gender their partners have been in the previous year and in their lifetime. By definition, we don’t see any “heterosexual” women who have had sex with a woman in the previous year or more than two women ever. The same goes for lesbian women having no sex with a man in the previous year and sex with not more than two men in their lifetime. Women who are not sexually active are, as we would expect, at 0 for both.

We can also look at how this splits out by self-reporting. We can see that identity doesn’t match behavior perfectly, so we see lesbians with higher #s of male partners and straight women with high #s of female partners.

Defining HPV

We identify HPV using the Vaginal swab data in NHANES categorized as

-High risk HPV 16,18,31,33,35,39,45,51,52,56,58,59,66 or

-Low risk HPV 6,11,26,40,42,53,54,55,61,62,64,67,68,69,70,71,72,73,81,82,83,84,IS39

-Any type (either high or low risk)

#Set everyone to zero
full_nhanes$any_hpv   <- 0 
full_nhanes$low_hpv   <- 0 
full_nhanes$high_hpv  <- 0 

#Create funcitons for both low and high risk that replace you with "1" if you have that strain and otherwise return the value you already have. 

#High Risk
f.high_risk           <- function(var) {
full_nhanes$any_hpv   <<- ifelse(var=="1", 1, full_nhanes$any_hpv) 
full_nhanes$high_hpv  <<- ifelse(var=="1", 1, full_nhanes$high_hpv) 
}

#Low Risk
f.low_risk            <- function(var) {
full_nhanes$any_hpv   <<- ifelse(var=="1", 1, full_nhanes$any_hpv) 
full_nhanes$low_hpv   <<- ifelse(var=="1", 1, full_nhanes$low_hpv) 
}

Analysis by Sexual Behavior Category

Now we use the survey-weighted data to compare prevalence of HPV by sexual behavior.

We compare by any, low risk, and high risk strains using first our primary definition of sexual behavior. We also calculate the mean number of sexual partners by sexual behavior category.

We then create both tables and graphs which we store to combine with other graphs later.

results_any        <- svyby(~any_hpv,  by=~behav, hpv_sample, svymean, na.rm=TRUE, vartype =c("ci", "se"))
